---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro'
---

<ProjectLayout
  badge="Competitive Robotics / October 2025"
  title="LARC 2025 at Tec de Monterrey. The Tracky Project."
  description="Built and raced a custom ESP32-C6 line-follower robot that recovers from 90° turns in milliseconds — engineered under real competition pressure at LARC 2025."
  coverImage="/portfolio/images/larc_arena.webp"
  coverAlt="Tracky robot racing at LARC 2025 arena, Tec de Monterrey"
  ogImage="https://alesso-24.github.io/portfolio/images/larc_arena.webp"
  meta={[
    { label: 'Role',  value: 'Hardware Lead & Software Co-Dev' },
    { label: 'Venue', value: 'Tec de Monterrey, N.L., Mexico' },
    { label: 'Event', value: 'LARC 2025 — TIR Line Follower Category' },
    { label: 'Date',  value: 'October 2025' },
  ]}
>

  <!-- Section 1: The Competition -->
  <h2 class="section-h2" data-reveal>The Competition Experience.</h2>

  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="80">
    Building hardware is one thing; making it survive a chaotic, high-stakes arena is another.
    At the 25th Latin American Robotics Competition (LARC) in Nuevo León, we put our engineering
    to the ultimate test. Facing off against top universities across Latin America in the TIR
    Line Follower category, we deployed our custom ESP32-C6 robot, Tracky, into a fiercely
    contested race where every millisecond mattered.
  </p>

  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="120">
    LARC 2025 wasn't just a showcase; it was an absolute proving ground. Held at the
    Tecnológico de Monterrey in Nuevo León, the environment was intense — filled with the smell
    of fresh solder, the high-pitch whine of racing servos, and teams pushing their hardware to
    the breaking point.
  </p>

  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="160">
    As a two-person team, agility was our best weapon. We were debugging C++ memory leaks on
    the fly, fighting BLE interference, and constantly recalibrating the IR arrays to match the
    arena's changing ambient light. It was real engineering under fire — where theoretical math
    meets physical reality, and your code either holds the line or crashes out.
  </p>

  <!-- Team photo -->
  <div data-reveal style="border-radius:18px; overflow:hidden; margin: clamp(32px,5vh,56px) 0; box-shadow: 0 22px 50px -30px rgba(234,106,46,0.35);">
    <img
      src="/portfolio/images/larc_team.webp"
      alt="Alessandro and teammate at LARC 2025"
      loading="lazy"
      decoding="async"
      style="width:100%; height:auto; display:block;"
    />
  </div>

  <hr class="divider" />

  <!-- Section 2: Engineering -->
  <h2 class="section-h2" data-reveal>Engineering Tracky for Performance.</h2>

  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="80">
    Tracky is built on low inertia and extreme processing speed. We ditched the standard Arduino
    loops and leveraged the ESP32-C6 (RISC-V core), implementing an RTOS-like architecture that
    guarantees our control loop fires instantly, making the robot hunt the line instead of just
    following it.
  </p>

  <!-- Tech cards -->
  <div class="tech-grid" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="120">
    <div class="tech-card">
      <h3>Inertial Recovery</h3>
      <p>
        Most line followers fail catastrophically on sharp 90° bends. We coded a Pure Inertial
        Recovery protocol: if all 8 IR sensors hit white, Tracky instantly pulls the derivative
        vector of its last known position and spins aggressively in that direction until it
        catches the track again.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="tech-card">
      <h3>Strat-Profiles</h3>
      <p>
        Reflashing code between heats is a rookie mistake. We wired physical DIP switches on
        the chassis to hot-swap between pre-calibrated PID profiles: Slow Test (Purple),
        Balanced (Blue), Aggressive (Red), and a High-Damping Mode (Green) for zig-zag sections.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="tech-card">
      <h3>BLE Auto-Healing</h3>
      <p>
        We built a real-time BLE dashboard in Python as a wireless "Optical Viewfinder" to tune
        PID parameters live. If the connection dropped due to arena interference, Tracky's
        Auto-Healing routine ignored the drop and continued the race autonomously.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="divider" />

  <!-- Section 3: Hardware -->
  <h2 class="section-h2" data-reveal>Hardware Integration.</h2>

  <div data-reveal data-reveal-delay="80" style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:16px;">
    {[
      'Swapped out inferior motor drivers to handle high-current burst maneuvers, ensuring the motors received clean PWM signals during aggressive cornering.',
      'Orchestrated a multiplexing circuit to poll all 8 phototransistors at lightning speed, feeding the PID error calculator with millimeter-perfect coordinates.',
      'ESP32-C6 served as the core brain, running concurrent RTOS-like logic to manage BLE telemetry, sensor polling, and kinematic math without blocking the main control loop.',
    ].map((item, i) => (
      <div style="display:flex; gap:16px; align-items:flex-start;">
        <span style="font-family:'Instrument Serif',serif; font-size:22px; color:#ea6a2e; flex-shrink:0; line-height:1.4;">{String(i + 1).padStart(2, '0')}</span>
        <p style="margin:0; font-size:clamp(14px,1.2vw,16px); line-height:1.65; color:#534f46;">{item}</p>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <!-- Robot full photo -->
  <div data-reveal style="border-radius:18px; overflow:hidden; margin: clamp(32px,5vh,56px) 0; box-shadow: 0 24px 60px -30px rgba(37,64,192,0.35);">
    <img
      src="/portfolio/images/robot_full.webp"
      alt="Tracky line follower robot full view"
      loading="lazy"
      decoding="async"
      style="width:100%; height:auto; display:block;"
    />
  </div>

</ProjectLayout>
